1
00:00:01,128 --> 00:00:04,820
sync & correction by f1nc0
~ Addic7ed.com ~

2
00:00:06,546 --> 00:00:10,346
Superheroes and Superman...

3
00:00:10,384 --> 00:00:12,618
they are one and the same.

4
00:00:12,620 --> 00:00:16,021
There are no other superheroes
without Superman, he's the first.

5
00:00:16,023 --> 00:00:20,626
An extraordinary being
with extraordinary powers.

6
00:00:20,628 --> 00:00:25,130
That was it. The whole
world of comic books changed.

7
00:00:25,132 --> 00:00:30,002
Superman is really
the all-father of superheroes.

8
00:00:30,004 --> 00:00:34,362
He is the Odin from which
all else springs forward.

9
00:00:35,275 --> 00:00:37,276
See, without Superman,

10
00:00:37,278 --> 00:00:41,013
there's no Marvel
or DC,

11
00:00:41,015 --> 00:00:43,215
no billion-dollar blockbusters.

12
00:00:46,019 --> 00:00:49,622
That logo is one of
the three most recognizable symbols

13
00:00:49,624 --> 00:00:52,892
on the planet,
and it stands shoulder to shoulder

14
00:00:52,894 --> 00:00:55,895
with the crucifix
and the Jewish star.

15
00:00:55,897 --> 00:00:59,198
Like, that's... madness, man!

16
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:03,200
Superman became
a worldwide phenomenon...

17
00:01:03,537 --> 00:01:09,174
and he was created by two
working-class kids from Cleveland...

18
00:01:09,176 --> 00:01:12,644
Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster.

19
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:17,516
Superman... he's for justice.

20
00:01:17,518 --> 00:01:19,151
It's kind of ironic

21
00:01:19,153 --> 00:01:24,344
that there was a great injustice
done to his creators.

22
00:01:24,458 --> 00:01:28,260
Siegel and Shuster
lost everything,

23
00:01:28,262 --> 00:01:30,629
and just like Superman...

24
00:01:31,431 --> 00:01:34,527
...they demanded justice.

25
00:01:34,528 --> 00:01:38,253
_

26
00:01:55,767 --> 00:01:59,273
_

27
00:02:02,595 --> 00:02:05,731
Cleveland, Ohio.
The late 1920s.

28
00:02:07,300 --> 00:02:10,436
To struggle is to be alive.

29
00:02:10,438 --> 00:02:12,538
Poverty is commonplace.

30
00:02:14,274 --> 00:02:18,210
And to be a dreamer...
is to be an outcast.

31
00:02:22,582 --> 00:02:26,582
Jerry Siegel is a dreamer...

32
00:02:26,587 --> 00:02:29,188
the son of working-class
Jewish immigrants.

33
00:02:30,323 --> 00:02:34,323
Jerry dreams of a world
outside of Ohio...

34
00:02:34,729 --> 00:02:38,397
one full of spacemen,
aliens,

35
00:02:38,399 --> 00:02:41,500
and creatures
from a planet far, far away.

36
00:02:42,635 --> 00:02:46,538
As kids play stickball,
Jerry prefers to stay inside.

37
00:02:48,174 --> 00:02:51,543
A typewriter is his main companion.

38
00:02:53,546 --> 00:02:57,282
Jerry Siegel...
he's a classic geek.

39
00:02:57,284 --> 00:03:02,429
You know... instead of liking
football or liking baseball,

40
00:03:02,464 --> 00:03:05,024
you know, he really
liked science fiction.

41
00:03:08,194 --> 00:03:10,362
I think it really was
escape for him,

42
00:03:10,364 --> 00:03:16,335
because he was very painfully
aware of how others thought of him.

43
00:03:19,039 --> 00:03:20,639
Back then,
people looked at him and said,

44
00:03:20,641 --> 00:03:22,681
"What? Comic books?

45
00:03:22,716 --> 00:03:26,592
You really think there's
a future in comic books?"

46
00:03:26,627 --> 00:03:29,715
At school, Jerry
is surrounded by classmates,

47
00:03:29,717 --> 00:03:32,684
and yet he feels alone.

48
00:03:32,686 --> 00:03:35,587
No one seems to "get" him...

49
00:03:35,589 --> 00:03:39,191
until the day
he meets Joe Shuster.

50
00:03:39,193 --> 00:03:41,760
- You all right?
- I'm fine.

51
00:03:41,762 --> 00:03:45,039
Um, you're Siegel, right?
I'm...

52
00:03:45,074 --> 00:03:48,467
Like Jerry, Joe
lives in a world of fantasy.

53
00:03:48,469 --> 00:03:51,270
The two boys are kindred spirits.

54
00:03:51,272 --> 00:03:55,607
- Is that Wonder Stories?
- Yeah. You know it?

55
00:03:55,609 --> 00:03:57,176
Yeah, uh...

56
00:03:57,178 --> 00:04:01,180
Joe was a super nerd too.
He was really small,

57
00:04:01,182 --> 00:04:04,149
really thin,
he wore the glasses.

58
00:04:04,151 --> 00:04:07,086
So he would get
all these self-help manuals

59
00:04:07,088 --> 00:04:09,288
through the mail
on how to get strong,

60
00:04:09,290 --> 00:04:12,130
and do all these exercises.

61
00:04:13,126 --> 00:04:15,794
He ate raw eggs
and lifted weights

62
00:04:15,796 --> 00:04:20,599
'cause he wanted to be this, like,
bigger person, and stronger...

63
00:04:20,601 --> 00:04:23,735
But the thing is,
it just never worked for him.

64
00:04:23,737 --> 00:04:26,538
He was still really thin,
really short,

65
00:04:26,540 --> 00:04:29,124
really kind of scrawny.

66
00:04:30,543 --> 00:04:32,377
Joe Shuster grew up very poor.

67
00:04:32,379 --> 00:04:35,547
In fact, Joe had to learn
to draw with gloves on.

68
00:04:35,549 --> 00:04:38,484
They couldn't afford heat.

69
00:04:38,486 --> 00:04:40,119
He would take
his mom's bread board

70
00:04:40,121 --> 00:04:43,422
when she was done making bread,
put a sheet of paper...

71
00:04:43,424 --> 00:04:44,556
or anything he could find,

72
00:04:44,558 --> 00:04:46,558
wallpaper,
scrap paper, anything,

73
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:48,894
and then he would
just draw on that.

74
00:04:48,896 --> 00:04:50,896
He was never really
taught how to draw,

75
00:04:50,898 --> 00:04:55,567
so he was self-taught,
but his eyesight was bad,

76
00:04:55,569 --> 00:04:58,737
so he would get
inches away from the paper

77
00:04:58,739 --> 00:05:00,839
and just scratch it out.

78
00:05:00,841 --> 00:05:02,908
These two guys
just hit it off together,

79
00:05:02,910 --> 00:05:07,467
and they worked on
the school newspaper together.

80
00:05:07,502 --> 00:05:09,906
They found
that they had a lot in common.

81
00:05:09,941 --> 00:05:14,620
An artist without a writer is as painful
as a writer without an artist.

82
00:05:14,622 --> 00:05:16,922
I mean, you can have
these great ideas,

83
00:05:16,924 --> 00:05:19,825
but if you can't translate them
somehow onto the page

84
00:05:19,827 --> 00:05:22,852
and show them to people,
what good are they?

85
00:05:22,887 --> 00:05:27,289
Joe was the perfect person
to translate Jerry's ideas.

86
00:05:27,324 --> 00:05:30,049
In high school, they
worked on the school newspaper,

87
00:05:30,084 --> 00:05:32,571
but they also
put together this magazine.

88
00:05:32,573 --> 00:05:35,340
They called it Science Fiction.

89
00:05:36,242 --> 00:05:38,510
One of the stories
in one of the issues

90
00:05:38,512 --> 00:05:41,214
is called
The Reign of the Super-Man.

91
00:05:41,548 --> 00:05:45,384
Jerry types down this real
pulpy science fiction story,

92
00:05:45,386 --> 00:05:47,853
Joe illustrates it,

93
00:05:47,855 --> 00:05:51,557
and the "super-man" in the story
is a bad guy,

94
00:05:51,559 --> 00:05:55,394
and he's bald, too, in the picture,
so he looks like Lex Luthor,

95
00:05:55,396 --> 00:05:58,297
and that story just doesn't work.

96
00:05:58,299 --> 00:06:01,833
They try to get people to buy
the magazine, and nobody buys it.

97
00:06:07,273 --> 00:06:10,309
And then, a seminal moment...

98
00:06:10,311 --> 00:06:13,412
Jerry's father passes away.

99
00:06:15,815 --> 00:06:20,604
He dies of a heart attack
while being robbed at gunpoint.

100
00:06:20,821 --> 00:06:24,821
Jerry never finds justice
for his father's killers...

101
00:06:24,858 --> 00:06:27,993
and it haunts him.

102
00:06:27,995 --> 00:06:30,295
Jerry really
had it tough after that,

103
00:06:30,297 --> 00:06:33,932
but he persisted, and that's
what Superman grew out of.

104
00:06:33,934 --> 00:06:36,935
There's no coincidence
that a year later,

105
00:06:36,937 --> 00:06:42,611
he creates Superman 's goal...
to eliminate crime.

106
00:06:44,510 --> 00:06:46,979
Maybe we did it wrong.

107
00:06:46,981 --> 00:06:49,715
We shouldn't have
made him a bad guy.

108
00:06:49,717 --> 00:06:51,250
What if he was good?

109
00:06:51,252 --> 00:06:54,286
He can do anything he wants,
but all he really wants

110
00:06:54,288 --> 00:06:58,790
is to... to fit in...
and help people.

111
00:06:58,792 --> 00:07:01,393
Any time
anybody creates something,

112
00:07:01,395 --> 00:07:04,329
there's always
that aspect of themselves

113
00:07:04,331 --> 00:07:07,132
that's in their characters.

114
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:11,400
You know, Joe, who was
small and couldn't get strong,

115
00:07:11,672 --> 00:07:14,657
that went into, you know,
creating someone

116
00:07:14,658 --> 00:07:18,510
who was big and strong,
like Superman.

117
00:07:18,512 --> 00:07:21,747
With Jerry, it was more personal.

118
00:07:21,749 --> 00:07:26,617
It was his father's death,
so Superman is really

119
00:07:26,618 --> 00:07:30,722
a kind of autobiography
for both of them.

120
00:07:30,724 --> 00:07:34,793
- Come here.
- What?

121
00:07:34,795 --> 00:07:37,562
Tell me what you think of this.

122
00:07:37,564 --> 00:07:39,464
That's our super-man!

123
00:07:47,707 --> 00:07:50,742
In 1933,
Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster

124
00:07:50,744 --> 00:07:54,744
create a character entirely unique...

125
00:07:55,381 --> 00:07:59,418
special powers,
a secret identity,

126
00:07:59,420 --> 00:08:01,753
a visitor from a distant planet.

127
00:08:01,755 --> 00:08:04,690
None of it had been seen before.

128
00:08:04,692 --> 00:08:07,626
See, in those days,
all comic strips

129
00:08:07,628 --> 00:08:11,630
are cowboys,
detectives,

130
00:08:11,632 --> 00:08:17,369
spacemen.
There is no such thing as superheroes.

131
00:08:17,371 --> 00:08:18,937
Jerry Siegel

132
00:08:18,939 --> 00:08:23,200
had been inventing mythology
since he was a teenager.

133
00:08:23,609 --> 00:08:28,569
Working with Joe, who was,
in many ways, his protégé,

134
00:08:28,615 --> 00:08:30,649
they developed Superman together,

135
00:08:30,651 --> 00:08:32,651
but it was a long gestation process.

136
00:08:32,653 --> 00:08:35,721
It took many, many, many years.

137
00:08:35,723 --> 00:08:37,889
When Siegel and Shuster
got started,

138
00:08:37,891 --> 00:08:39,424
what they really wanted to do

139
00:08:39,426 --> 00:08:42,279
was be able to sell a comic strip...

140
00:08:42,495 --> 00:08:44,730
because back in the 1930s,

141
00:08:44,732 --> 00:08:49,468
the real rock stars of the comics
world were comic strip artists.

142
00:08:49,470 --> 00:08:52,037
Like Milton Caniff
or Rube Goldberg,

143
00:08:52,039 --> 00:08:54,539
or E.C. Segar, who did Popeye,

144
00:08:54,541 --> 00:08:56,441
they were the celebrities of their time.

145
00:08:56,443 --> 00:08:58,877
They were on the front of magazines

146
00:08:58,879 --> 00:09:01,580
and they met with presidents.

147
00:09:01,582 --> 00:09:03,415
At that point, newspaper comics,

148
00:09:03,417 --> 00:09:06,084
that was the way
to make a lot of money.

149
00:09:06,086 --> 00:09:09,621
So they sent their Superman
to all these syndicates,

150
00:09:09,623 --> 00:09:12,457
and they got them back
with rejection notices.

151
00:09:12,892 --> 00:09:14,459
They couldn't sell it to anybody,

152
00:09:14,461 --> 00:09:17,796
because any time
you have a new idea,

153
00:09:17,798 --> 00:09:20,832
everybody thinks it's stupid.

154
00:09:20,834 --> 00:09:23,034
You know, they said,
"Joe can't draw,"

155
00:09:23,036 --> 00:09:25,036
"Jerry has no business writing,"

156
00:09:25,038 --> 00:09:27,939
and somebody said,
"No one will ever believe this stuff."

157
00:09:27,941 --> 00:09:30,509
Let's look at the heroes
who existed prior to Superman.

158
00:09:30,511 --> 00:09:32,771
You had, like, your Flash Gordon,
your Buck Rogers.

159
00:09:32,806 --> 00:09:34,713
You know, Flash Gordon,
at the end of the day,

160
00:09:34,715 --> 00:09:38,116
was a guy who, like, you know,
hey, he luckily got to space.

161
00:09:38,118 --> 00:09:39,851
He didn't have any superpowers.

162
00:09:39,853 --> 00:09:42,521
Buck Rogers... just a guy
who went to the future.

163
00:09:42,523 --> 00:09:44,089
Didn't have any superpowers.

164
00:09:44,091 --> 00:09:47,426
But that genre would be
reinvented by Superman

165
00:09:47,428 --> 00:09:49,561
because he's a god,

166
00:09:49,563 --> 00:09:53,943
he's this strange visitor from
another planet with these abilities.

167
00:09:54,767 --> 00:09:57,736
But newspapers were saying
"It's too far-fetched,"

168
00:09:57,738 --> 00:10:01,738
"It's silly," and they felt that
this concept of a super-man

169
00:10:01,809 --> 00:10:04,576
would never take off.

170
00:10:04,578 --> 00:10:08,547
And, in the meantime,
they did get comic book work,

171
00:10:08,549 --> 00:10:11,183
and so they were getting paid.

172
00:10:11,185 --> 00:10:13,218
They were doing, uh, Dr. Occult.

173
00:10:13,220 --> 00:10:17,860
They were doing, uh, a lot of
federal agent-type strips.

174
00:10:18,559 --> 00:10:20,459
They were actually
building up a reputation

175
00:10:20,461 --> 00:10:24,461
in this new comic industry.

176
00:10:24,531 --> 00:10:26,698
Prior to Superman,
I don't know that you could say

177
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:28,033
there was a comic book business.

178
00:10:28,035 --> 00:10:31,036
What there was...
was a publishing business.

179
00:10:31,038 --> 00:10:32,904
There were pulp magazines.

180
00:10:32,906 --> 00:10:34,806
There were comic strips,

181
00:10:34,808 --> 00:10:38,243
which were the most popular
part of the newspapers,

182
00:10:38,245 --> 00:10:40,946
and there were people
that were entrepreneurial,

183
00:10:40,948 --> 00:10:43,582
in a way,
that tried to marry the two.

184
00:10:43,584 --> 00:10:46,952
Ultimately, Superman
resided in the slush pile

185
00:10:46,954 --> 00:10:50,954
until Harry Donenfeld
and Jack Liebowitz said,

186
00:10:51,225 --> 00:10:53,124
"Let's give it a shot."

187
00:10:53,126 --> 00:10:56,962
- What about that one?
- Can't put that on the cover.

188
00:10:56,964 --> 00:10:58,029
It's a good story.

189
00:10:58,031 --> 00:11:01,032
Doesn't matter.
It's not gonna sell magazines.

190
00:11:01,034 --> 00:11:06,171
Harry Donenfeld and
Jack Liebowitz run DC Comics.

191
00:11:06,173 --> 00:11:10,173
Donenfeld is a showman,
a bit outlandish.

192
00:11:10,544 --> 00:11:14,544
Jack Liebowitz is mild-mannered,
more even-tempered.

193
00:11:15,616 --> 00:11:20,752
Both men share a common bond... money.

194
00:11:20,754 --> 00:11:24,122
But in 1937, business is bad,

195
00:11:24,124 --> 00:11:26,992
and they are willing to take a risk.

196
00:11:27,927 --> 00:11:31,336
What about that strip those
guys from Cleveland sent in?

197
00:11:36,602 --> 00:11:37,836
Here it is.

198
00:11:39,672 --> 00:11:44,075
- Superman.
- Superman, huh?

199
00:11:44,077 --> 00:11:47,746
Harry and Jack were entrepreneurs.

200
00:11:47,748 --> 00:11:49,614
They were just trying
to sell magazines.

201
00:11:49,616 --> 00:11:51,583
They were just
trying to make a buck.

202
00:11:51,585 --> 00:11:54,819
Let's get a contract
written up right away.

203
00:11:54,821 --> 00:11:57,822
I'll have one sent out
for them to sign immediately.

204
00:11:57,824 --> 00:12:00,559
And the letter
is sent to Jerry and Joe,

205
00:12:00,561 --> 00:12:05,433
offering the grand sum total
of $10 a page,

206
00:12:05,468 --> 00:12:10,219
and there's 13 pages,
so it was 130 bucks.

207
00:12:12,038 --> 00:12:15,223
That Superman idea,
which had originally been formatted

208
00:12:15,256 --> 00:12:19,311
as a comic strip, they said,
"Reformat those strips into a 13-page story."

209
00:12:25,618 --> 00:12:27,419
The thing
that you have to remember

210
00:12:27,454 --> 00:12:29,754
is that the process of creation,

211
00:12:29,756 --> 00:12:33,258
you're putting
all of your energy into that.

212
00:12:33,260 --> 00:12:36,227
You don't think about
if somebody's gonna cheat you.

213
00:12:36,229 --> 00:12:39,138
You just hope
somebody's going to print it.

214
00:12:40,066 --> 00:12:43,268
I told Donenfeld we'd have this
back to him by tomorrow.

215
00:12:43,270 --> 00:12:44,703
You know, maybe they want to do

216
00:12:44,705 --> 00:12:46,371
The Crimson Horsemen instead.

217
00:12:46,373 --> 00:12:50,875
No, they want action.
They want Superman.

218
00:12:50,877 --> 00:12:55,280
When we sign, we'll get our check.
$130.

219
00:12:56,248 --> 00:12:59,017
Here, let me see that again.

220
00:12:59,019 --> 00:13:02,187
Remember,
this process took years.

221
00:13:02,189 --> 00:13:07,892
They had sent Superman to every
publisher. Nobody liked it.

222
00:13:07,894 --> 00:13:10,061
If Jerry
and Joe sign the deal,

223
00:13:10,063 --> 00:13:15,166
their character, Superman, will
be known throughout the world.

224
00:13:15,168 --> 00:13:19,168
It's a dream they've had
since they were kids...

225
00:13:19,339 --> 00:13:26,098
But if they sign, they also give up
all rights to the Superman character.

226
00:13:29,715 --> 00:13:32,594
Okay, give me a pen.

227
00:13:32,652 --> 00:13:36,121
Signing the deal
will change both men forever...

228
00:13:36,123 --> 00:13:40,687
as Superman will become
a worldwide phenomenon.

229
00:13:44,330 --> 00:13:46,731
With World War II looming,

230
00:13:46,733 --> 00:13:49,701
the United States needs a hero,

231
00:13:49,703 --> 00:13:53,438
someone who represents the
very best of American values...

232
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:58,410
truth, liberty, justice.

233
00:13:58,412 --> 00:14:01,980
When Superman came along,
America was desperate

234
00:14:01,982 --> 00:14:04,683
for a dream they could believe in.

235
00:14:04,685 --> 00:14:07,919
Any story that could
touch them deep down

236
00:14:07,921 --> 00:14:10,722
in a way that made them
feel that things might be okay

237
00:14:10,724 --> 00:14:12,290
was going to ignite,

238
00:14:12,292 --> 00:14:15,193
and Superman
happened to be that story.

239
00:14:15,195 --> 00:14:19,030
Back then, nobody knew
who or what Superman was.

240
00:14:19,032 --> 00:14:21,833
They'd just see this guy
in the tights

241
00:14:21,835 --> 00:14:24,469
and he's lifting this car
over his head,

242
00:14:24,471 --> 00:14:29,207
and that was it...
we have the first superhero.

243
00:14:29,209 --> 00:14:31,309
Within three months,

244
00:14:31,311 --> 00:14:35,180
Superman sold a million copies.

245
00:14:35,182 --> 00:14:39,025
Once that happened...
Boom! Everything blew up.

246
00:14:39,985 --> 00:14:43,755
I was a kid at that period,
and he was my hero.

247
00:14:43,757 --> 00:14:46,753
I mean, it was phenomenal.

248
00:14:46,788 --> 00:14:48,359
Superman
is celebrated within a year

249
00:14:48,361 --> 00:14:51,196
at the New York World's Fair in 1939.

250
00:14:51,198 --> 00:14:53,865
You have Superman
appearing in the Macy's parade.

251
00:14:53,867 --> 00:14:57,035
You have Superman starting to show
up in comic strips and on radio.

252
00:14:57,037 --> 00:15:00,438
- Look! Up in the sky!
- It's a bird! It's a plane!

253
00:15:00,440 --> 00:15:02,373
It's Superman!

254
00:15:02,375 --> 00:15:05,176
Max Fleischer
wanted to do Superman cartoons,

255
00:15:05,178 --> 00:15:07,479
so they did Superman cartoons.

256
00:15:07,481 --> 00:15:09,981
It was an early licensing bonanza.

257
00:15:09,983 --> 00:15:12,217
There was costumes,
there was toys,

258
00:15:12,219 --> 00:15:14,786
there was all kinds of spin-offs.

259
00:15:17,423 --> 00:15:20,525
They didn't own the character,
but they got paid for it,

260
00:15:20,527 --> 00:15:24,350
so Jerry and Joe
got to do their comic strip.

261
00:15:25,097 --> 00:15:27,766
Superman
was showing up everywhere,

262
00:15:27,768 --> 00:15:30,235
so they were doin' great.

263
00:15:30,237 --> 00:15:36,331
They built a studio for Joe,
and they were able to bring in

264
00:15:36,366 --> 00:15:39,059
other artists to help Joe,
because there was no way

265
00:15:39,094 --> 00:15:41,346
he could turn out more than
one or two books a month,

266
00:15:41,348 --> 00:15:45,348
so, uh, he would oversee
these guys drawing Superman.

267
00:15:45,385 --> 00:15:48,981
Curl in the front of the forehead...
That's good.

268
00:15:49,016 --> 00:15:50,822
- Joe, take a look at this.
- Yeah, just like that.

269
00:15:50,824 --> 00:15:53,858
- Joe, so in this next scene...
- Right, this is the train...

270
00:15:53,860 --> 00:15:56,027
- Now, this train has got to be huge.
- Yeah.

271
00:15:56,029 --> 00:15:57,195
They're doing very good.

272
00:15:58,798 --> 00:16:00,799
They were celebrities.

273
00:16:00,801 --> 00:16:03,268
You know, Superman's creators,
Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster.

274
00:16:03,270 --> 00:16:05,906
So it was a good life.

275
00:16:08,174 --> 00:16:10,975
In 1940, there's a famous
Saturday Evening Post article

276
00:16:10,977 --> 00:16:13,278
where Siegel and Shuster
are held up

277
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:18,089
as these icons of American success.

278
00:16:18,124 --> 00:16:21,820
Now, our guest tonight
is the man who originated Superman.

279
00:16:21,822 --> 00:16:23,288
He's Mr. Jerry Siegel.

280
00:16:23,290 --> 00:16:28,466
- Good evening, Fred.
- Now, how does he change his clothes so fast?

281
00:16:28,501 --> 00:16:31,145
Well, after all,
he's Superman, Fred.

282
00:16:34,366 --> 00:16:36,868
Jerry and Joe
are being paid well,

283
00:16:36,870 --> 00:16:39,904
but not nearly well enough.

284
00:16:39,906 --> 00:16:44,442
Donenfeld and Liebowitz are making
millions off their creation...

285
00:16:44,444 --> 00:16:50,749
And as Superman's popularity grows,
so does the workload.

286
00:16:50,951 --> 00:16:55,954
To Jerry and Joe...
it's just not right.

287
00:16:55,956 --> 00:17:00,091
They were very unhappy
with what was an inequitable deal.

288
00:17:00,093 --> 00:17:03,127
Something
as phenomenally successful

289
00:17:03,129 --> 00:17:04,996
and wonderful as Superman,

290
00:17:04,998 --> 00:17:08,998
it rankled Jerry and Joe
not getting their fair share.

291
00:17:09,469 --> 00:17:12,370
They didn't get royalties,
really, essentially,

292
00:17:12,372 --> 00:17:16,976
so, as the writer-creator
of Superman...

293
00:17:17,444 --> 00:17:19,932
it would get you mad.

294
00:17:27,953 --> 00:17:29,487
The bombing of Pearl Harbor

295
00:17:29,489 --> 00:17:32,023
forces America into World War II.

296
00:17:35,628 --> 00:17:38,296
Jerry is drafted to the Army,

297
00:17:38,298 --> 00:17:42,298
while Joe stays home
due to his poor eyesight.

298
00:17:42,335 --> 00:17:46,537
For the first time,
someone else writes Superman,

299
00:17:46,539 --> 00:17:50,937
and Jerry isn't as valued
as he once was.

300
00:17:52,211 --> 00:17:56,157
During the war, Superman
is more popular than ever.

301
00:17:57,049 --> 00:18:00,118
He's an American ally,

302
00:18:00,120 --> 00:18:02,587
battling villains
both real and imagined.

303
00:18:07,993 --> 00:18:12,096
Really, what he did
was motivated people

304
00:18:12,098 --> 00:18:14,499
to become a part of the war effort.

305
00:18:14,501 --> 00:18:16,100
Perhaps most famously,

306
00:18:16,102 --> 00:18:21,585
he was the most widely read
periodical on Army bases.

307
00:18:21,620 --> 00:18:24,709
G.I.s and airmen
were putting him

308
00:18:24,711 --> 00:18:26,644
on their tanks and on their Jeeps

309
00:18:26,646 --> 00:18:28,613
and on their airplane nose cones

310
00:18:28,615 --> 00:18:32,997
as a myth that they carried
with them and identified with

311
00:18:33,032 --> 00:18:35,985
that gave them courage in battle.

312
00:18:35,989 --> 00:18:39,290
Superman
is pure propaganda...

313
00:18:39,292 --> 00:18:41,592
and the public can't get enough.

314
00:18:41,932 --> 00:18:44,880
DC Comics capitalizes...

315
00:18:45,064 --> 00:18:48,007
with a Superboy spin-off.

316
00:18:48,467 --> 00:18:54,055
Jerry had pitched Superboy
many years earlier.

317
00:18:55,107 --> 00:18:57,342
He presented this idea,

318
00:18:57,344 --> 00:19:00,539
the adventures of Superman
when he was a boy,

319
00:19:00,574 --> 00:19:02,714
called it Superboy...

320
00:19:02,716 --> 00:19:07,016
and he was told by his editors,
"stupid idea."

321
00:19:07,753 --> 00:19:10,121
While he was in the army,

322
00:19:10,123 --> 00:19:13,624
DC Comics decided,
"Let's do Superboy."

323
00:19:13,626 --> 00:19:16,127
They were in touch with Joe,

324
00:19:16,129 --> 00:19:21,175
but they didn't tell Jerry
or ask his permission.

325
00:19:21,267 --> 00:19:24,402
During the war,
Jerry met a, uh, an attorney,

326
00:19:24,404 --> 00:19:27,873
who convinced him
that they should sue DC

327
00:19:27,874 --> 00:19:32,610
to get out of their contract and try
to get more of a piece of Superman.

328
00:19:32,612 --> 00:19:36,581
You're a lawyer.
They can't do this, right?

329
00:19:36,583 --> 00:19:39,584
No.
No, they can't.

330
00:19:39,586 --> 00:19:44,555
- So what can I do?
- Sue.

331
00:19:44,557 --> 00:19:48,546
He sees himself
not only ripped off, but he thinks,

332
00:19:48,581 --> 00:19:51,663
"This is a sign they want to
take away everything from me,"

333
00:19:51,664 --> 00:19:54,964
so he's going to pursue justice.

334
00:19:59,438 --> 00:20:03,438
Jerry Siegel comes home
from World War II on a mission.

335
00:20:03,443 --> 00:20:05,710
It's 1947.

336
00:20:05,712 --> 00:20:09,447
He's suing DC Comics
for the rights to Superman,

337
00:20:09,449 --> 00:20:13,449
and he convinces Joe Shuster
to do the same.

338
00:20:13,553 --> 00:20:17,553
Jerry is confident
that justice is on his side.

339
00:20:17,824 --> 00:20:21,459
It's a gamble that could
cost both men everything.

340
00:20:21,461 --> 00:20:26,335
The risk was being banned,
basically, from DC after that.

341
00:20:26,370 --> 00:20:28,599
It is the opinion of this court

342
00:20:28,601 --> 00:20:31,669
that the plaintiffs,
Mr. Siegel and Mr. Shuster,

343
00:20:31,671 --> 00:20:33,438
transferred all of their rights

344
00:20:33,440 --> 00:20:36,774
in, and to,
the comic strip Superman,

345
00:20:36,776 --> 00:20:43,314
including the title, names, characters,
and concept to the defendant.

346
00:20:43,316 --> 00:20:48,553
This court affirms that the defendant
is the sole and exclusive owner

347
00:20:48,555 --> 00:20:51,189
of the character Superman.

348
00:20:51,191 --> 00:20:52,857
This court is adjourned.

349
00:20:56,261 --> 00:20:57,728
They lose that case.

350
00:20:57,730 --> 00:21:00,565
They do not get Superman back...

351
00:21:02,234 --> 00:21:06,955
But it then goes on to say
that the Superboy character

352
00:21:06,956 --> 00:21:09,674
was indeed created by Jerry Siegel.

353
00:21:09,676 --> 00:21:12,443
DC Comics should have
bought that character from him,

354
00:21:12,445 --> 00:21:14,645
so they enter into a settlement.

355
00:21:14,647 --> 00:21:17,782
They got a settlement,
but it went to all the lawyers,

356
00:21:17,784 --> 00:21:22,616
and they were fired from
working on Superman at DC.

357
00:21:22,822 --> 00:21:26,424
There's this really
strange thing that Jerry says.

358
00:21:26,426 --> 00:21:33,151
He's in the courtroom, and he
looks over and he sees Superman...

359
00:21:34,300 --> 00:21:37,768
and he disappears.

360
00:21:39,872 --> 00:21:41,839
He knows
that this is the moment

361
00:21:41,841 --> 00:21:45,776
where this thing
they'd worked so hard on

362
00:21:45,778 --> 00:21:48,646
has been taken away...

363
00:21:48,648 --> 00:21:54,524
and now they've been barred
from the character they created.

364
00:21:55,287 --> 00:21:57,605
They're devastated by it,

365
00:21:57,606 --> 00:22:01,325
but they're together,
and they say,

366
00:22:01,327 --> 00:22:04,929
"Let's just do it again.
Let's do something better.

367
00:22:04,931 --> 00:22:08,499
Lightning can strike twice."

368
00:22:08,501 --> 00:22:12,501
And so,
they come up with Funnyman.

369
00:22:12,772 --> 00:22:13,999
They took the humor of, like,

370
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:17,529
Danny Kaye's movies and
combined it with Superman,

371
00:22:17,564 --> 00:22:21,480
but the jokes weren't very funny
and he wasn't all that super,

372
00:22:21,515 --> 00:22:24,916
and that fell flat after
about a half a dozen issues.

373
00:22:24,918 --> 00:22:28,452
People were expecting
another Superman,

374
00:22:28,454 --> 00:22:31,656
and it was as far from
Superman as could be...

375
00:22:33,425 --> 00:22:36,861
And I think that's where
they really felt it.

376
00:22:36,863 --> 00:22:41,500
"Not only did we lose Superman,
but we lost the spark.

377
00:22:41,668 --> 00:22:45,942
What do we have now?"

378
00:22:45,977 --> 00:22:48,773
In hindsight, they should've
never filed the '47 lawsuit,

379
00:22:48,775 --> 00:22:52,643
because in 1948, it did appear
that they were going to get

380
00:22:52,645 --> 00:22:54,645
another renewal of their contract,

381
00:22:54,647 --> 00:22:56,781
and if they'd taken that renewal,

382
00:22:56,783 --> 00:23:01,260
that would've taken them
into the Superman TV show.

383
00:23:01,295 --> 00:23:03,588
The Adventures of Superman!

384
00:23:03,590 --> 00:23:07,291
That would've taken them
to a whole new era of merchandising.

385
00:23:07,293 --> 00:23:09,273
They could've been set for life.

386
00:23:09,308 --> 00:23:12,463
More powerful
than a locomotive...

387
00:23:12,465 --> 00:23:16,434
The 1950s sees the
dawn of a new visual medium,

388
00:23:16,436 --> 00:23:20,436
and once again
Superman is a sensation.

389
00:23:20,440 --> 00:23:22,707
Alongside I Love Lucy,

390
00:23:22,709 --> 00:23:27,612
The Adventures of Superman is one
of the biggest hits on television.

391
00:23:27,614 --> 00:23:30,565
There can only be one Superman,
of course, but did you ever

392
00:23:30,566 --> 00:23:34,721
think about some of the super
things that you can do for yourself?

393
00:23:34,756 --> 00:23:37,519
Kids were completely enamored of it,

394
00:23:37,857 --> 00:23:40,391
but also a lot of adults were, too.

395
00:23:40,393 --> 00:23:45,296
The idea of someone
who's the best version of ourselves

396
00:23:45,298 --> 00:23:48,666
was very appealing
to us as a society,

397
00:23:48,668 --> 00:23:51,469
especially at the end of World War II.

398
00:23:51,471 --> 00:23:53,537
Here was a guy
who had all this power,

399
00:23:53,539 --> 00:23:56,474
and, unlike people with power
who abuse it,

400
00:23:56,476 --> 00:23:58,542
Superman never abused his power,

401
00:23:58,544 --> 00:24:02,813
and people just really gravitated to it,
so it was a huge hit.

402
00:24:02,815 --> 00:24:04,515
Yes, it's Superman!

403
00:24:04,517 --> 00:24:05,983
The strange visitor
from another planet

404
00:24:05,985 --> 00:24:08,319
who came to Earth
with powers and abilities

405
00:24:08,321 --> 00:24:10,388
far beyond those of mortal men.

406
00:24:10,390 --> 00:24:13,165
Superman, who...

407
00:24:14,760 --> 00:24:16,360
Do you know how many people
are watching this right now?

408
00:24:16,362 --> 00:24:18,442
- Jerry...
- Do you know how much that

409
00:24:18,443 --> 00:24:21,164
George Reeves makes?
How much those crooks,

410
00:24:21,199 --> 00:24:23,334
Donenfeld and Liebowitz,
make off of what we did?

411
00:24:23,336 --> 00:24:26,394
There wouldn't even be
a Superman if it wasn't for us.

412
00:24:26,429 --> 00:24:29,227
How is it that we're sitting
here with nothing?

413
00:24:29,609 --> 00:24:33,144
There's never going
to be another Superman, Joe.

414
00:24:33,979 --> 00:24:36,681
Things for Jerry
got really bad really fast.

415
00:24:36,683 --> 00:24:38,620
He couldn't get work.

416
00:24:38,917 --> 00:24:44,488
His wife, Joanne...
she had Jerry's conviction that

417
00:24:44,490 --> 00:24:48,059
there was an injustice done.

418
00:24:48,061 --> 00:24:51,495
Joanne Siegel was Lois Lane.

419
00:24:51,497 --> 00:24:54,932
She was the physical model
for Lois Lane, first of all,

420
00:24:54,934 --> 00:24:58,536
but more important, later in life,

421
00:24:58,538 --> 00:25:01,539
she was kind of sticking up for Jerry

422
00:25:01,541 --> 00:25:05,376
at a time when he wasn't
sticking up for himself.

423
00:25:05,378 --> 00:25:08,379
Joanne called DC Comics

424
00:25:08,381 --> 00:25:10,614
and tried to shame them
into giving Jerry a job

425
00:25:10,616 --> 00:25:13,918
so he could at least make some
money to keep his family going.

426
00:25:13,920 --> 00:25:16,617
Thank you.

427
00:25:17,689 --> 00:25:20,493
Jerry gets hired as a staff writer.

428
00:25:23,428 --> 00:25:25,663
No celebration of his return.

429
00:25:25,665 --> 00:25:29,665
He's just this anonymous... writer.

430
00:25:30,703 --> 00:25:32,903
Even though Jerry was told,

431
00:25:32,905 --> 00:25:36,540
"We'll never put your name
on these issues.

432
00:25:36,542 --> 00:25:38,109
No one will ever know you wrote it,"

433
00:25:38,111 --> 00:25:43,047
he still found a way
to get his voice into the stories.

434
00:25:43,049 --> 00:25:44,982
I mean, he would write
these wonderful stories

435
00:25:44,984 --> 00:25:48,301
of going back to Krypton.

436
00:25:49,121 --> 00:25:51,155
Superman's return to Krypton,

437
00:25:51,157 --> 00:25:52,857
I think that played into the fantasy

438
00:25:52,859 --> 00:25:56,527
of "Well, if you could fix your life,
if you could go back

439
00:25:56,562 --> 00:25:58,805
and do things over again,
what would you do?"

440
00:25:58,840 --> 00:26:00,739
and here was Superman going back

441
00:26:00,740 --> 00:26:03,968
and trying to save his parents
and finding that things

442
00:26:03,969 --> 00:26:06,604
were not as simple
as he thought they were,

443
00:26:06,606 --> 00:26:10,324
and that ultimately he failed anyway.

444
00:26:11,477 --> 00:26:14,745
There's a funnier story;
Superboy 100,

445
00:26:14,747 --> 00:26:17,148
a milestone issue of the character,

446
00:26:17,150 --> 00:26:20,401
and Superboy's parents come
back, but it turns out that his

447
00:26:20,402 --> 00:26:23,652
parents are evil pretenders
who are not really his parents,

448
00:26:23,689 --> 00:26:26,157
which is a clear jibe
at Jerry Siegel's belief

449
00:26:26,159 --> 00:26:29,460
that he's the true creator
of Superboy...

450
00:26:29,462 --> 00:26:35,785
so he sneaks in these interesting
little jabs at the company.

451
00:26:37,135 --> 00:26:39,036
With Jerry writing for DC,

452
00:26:39,038 --> 00:26:43,808
Joe earns money as an artist...
but not drawing comic books.

453
00:26:43,810 --> 00:26:47,011
What he's doing isn't for kids.

454
00:26:48,580 --> 00:26:53,525
He actually started
doing S&M fetish drawings.

455
00:26:54,187 --> 00:26:56,654
They were the pornography
of their time,

456
00:26:56,656 --> 00:26:58,189
these under-the-counter pulps

457
00:26:58,191 --> 00:27:02,191
that had very racy
inside artwork and stories.

458
00:27:02,228 --> 00:27:05,729
Whether he was specifically
trying to look like

459
00:27:05,731 --> 00:27:10,468
the Superman family as a kind
of a revenge against DC Comics

460
00:27:10,470 --> 00:27:13,003
in these illustrated booklets
that he did,

461
00:27:13,005 --> 00:27:14,672
called Nights of Horror,

462
00:27:14,674 --> 00:27:17,708
I couldn't say, but that's
what Joe had been doing

463
00:27:17,710 --> 00:27:22,813
in those kind of lost years that
nobody knew how he was getting by.

464
00:27:22,815 --> 00:27:25,015
Joe was a jobber.

465
00:27:25,017 --> 00:27:26,717
He had an assignment,
he was gonna do it...

466
00:27:26,719 --> 00:27:31,635
But for Jerry, he felt like
he never had what he deserved.

467
00:27:31,670 --> 00:27:33,757
Jerry was back
working at DC,

468
00:27:33,759 --> 00:27:35,626
and had a rough time of it.

469
00:27:35,628 --> 00:27:38,262
Hey, Siegel. How are
those changes coming along?

470
00:27:38,264 --> 00:27:41,799
I'm just finishing them up
right now, sir.

471
00:27:41,801 --> 00:27:44,068
Jerry would go in and say,

472
00:27:44,070 --> 00:27:48,070
"Hey, I've got an idea about
Superman does this and that."

473
00:27:48,107 --> 00:27:53,530
Sir? Did you get my story
about Krypton I sent you?

474
00:27:54,613 --> 00:27:58,960
It's not gonna work.
Just stick to what the editor gave you.

475
00:27:58,995 --> 00:28:02,130
And he would actually trade
the story off to another writer

476
00:28:02,165 --> 00:28:03,423
and kind of make it as if it were him,

477
00:28:03,458 --> 00:28:06,174
which is sort of the worst
thing you can do to a writer.

478
00:28:06,209 --> 00:28:09,560
It kind of demoralizes them.
It was tough.

479
00:28:09,562 --> 00:28:13,562
So, Jerry Siegel persuades Joe
to go in with him

480
00:28:13,733 --> 00:28:17,668
to try to get Superman back...
again.

481
00:28:17,670 --> 00:28:22,755
For Jerry, the risk was being let go
and losing his writer job,

482
00:28:22,790 --> 00:28:27,043
but he had this core conviction
that they were being mistreated,

483
00:28:27,078 --> 00:28:31,702
and until he had that judgment,
he was not going to be happy.

484
00:28:38,123 --> 00:28:42,932
In 1967,
a new copyright law is enacted.

485
00:28:43,162 --> 00:28:46,931
Jerry and Joe sue again,

486
00:28:46,933 --> 00:28:50,755
trying to regain the rights
to Superman.

487
00:28:51,102 --> 00:28:52,636
We are persuaded here

488
00:28:52,638 --> 00:28:56,006
that the court judgment
of May 21, 1948

489
00:28:56,008 --> 00:28:59,710
effectively stopped
Mr. Siegel and Mr. Shuster

490
00:28:59,712 --> 00:29:01,612
from contesting the issue

491
00:29:01,614 --> 00:29:03,981
of ownership of copyright
of Superman.

492
00:29:03,983 --> 00:29:09,153
What they found was
that the Superboy settlement

493
00:29:09,155 --> 00:29:12,656
had effectively closed the door
on any other litigation.

494
00:29:12,658 --> 00:29:15,125
This precludes the
plaintiffs from contesting...

495
00:29:15,127 --> 00:29:18,696
Leaving Jerry and Joe
without a job,

496
00:29:18,698 --> 00:29:23,233
and without any other possibility
of opening it up again.

497
00:29:23,235 --> 00:29:28,172
- ...the defendants, DC Comics.
- They were out of comics.

498
00:29:28,174 --> 00:29:34,252
They were kind of out of everything.
They were pretty bleak times.

499
00:29:35,013 --> 00:29:40,020
Joe is in New York,
unmarried, without children.

500
00:29:40,055 --> 00:29:42,987
He stays in his brother's
one-bedroom apartment,

501
00:29:42,989 --> 00:29:46,366
scraping by even to survive.

502
00:29:47,058 --> 00:29:48,892
He slept on a cot,

503
00:29:48,894 --> 00:29:52,196
next to a window
that had no curtains...

504
00:29:52,198 --> 00:29:56,646
and had tape
on the broken cracks.

505
00:29:57,902 --> 00:30:01,739
The artist of Superman...

506
00:30:01,741 --> 00:30:04,597
sleeping on a cot.

507
00:30:05,411 --> 00:30:10,594
In wintertime, he couldn't afford,
uh, to buy an overcoat.

508
00:30:10,629 --> 00:30:15,152
For a period of time,
he was a messenger in Manhattan...

509
00:30:16,388 --> 00:30:19,891
And one of his deliveries was
to DC Comics, and he came in

510
00:30:19,926 --> 00:30:22,758
and saw the big painting
of Superman there.

511
00:30:22,962 --> 00:30:25,095
Here he was,
delivering packages.

512
00:30:25,097 --> 00:30:30,518
Can you sign this, please?
Line 17. Right there.

513
00:30:30,553 --> 00:30:32,506
Meanwhile, the people
that were now taking over

514
00:30:32,534 --> 00:30:34,438
Superman were doing
very well for themselves.

515
00:30:34,440 --> 00:30:38,275
- The Sanchez file.
- Hello, Mr. Liebowitz.

516
00:30:38,277 --> 00:30:43,013
Jack Liebowitz said,
"What are you doing around here?"

517
00:30:43,015 --> 00:30:46,383
- He said, "Delivering messages."
- Delivery?

518
00:30:46,385 --> 00:30:51,976
- "You don't have a coat."
- Oh, I don't mind the cold.

519
00:30:54,726 --> 00:30:58,577
You buy yourself a warm coat,
you hear me?

520
00:30:58,612 --> 00:31:02,190
Thank you, Mr. Liebowitz.

521
00:31:03,101 --> 00:31:08,542
There's too many
stories like this. Bad stories.

522
00:31:15,080 --> 00:31:19,490
Jerry is married with
one daughter in Southern California.

523
00:31:21,786 --> 00:31:24,648
He works as a postal clerk.

524
00:31:25,757 --> 00:31:31,160
Very few are aware that he created
the most iconic hero of our time.

525
00:31:33,679 --> 00:31:37,267
Then something happens
that makes Jerry snap,

526
00:31:37,269 --> 00:31:43,258
and it's the news that they're
going to make a Superman movie.

527
00:31:43,341 --> 00:31:47,811
It's going to be this huge blockbuster
with Marlon Brando.

528
00:31:47,813 --> 00:31:50,247
Mario Puzo, the guy
who wrote The Godfather movie's

529
00:31:50,249 --> 00:31:53,851
getting paid
to write the Superman movie,

530
00:31:53,853 --> 00:31:58,935
which Jerry Siegel sees...
and he loses it.

531
00:31:58,970 --> 00:32:01,738
Here's a guy that created Superman.

532
00:32:01,773 --> 00:32:05,062
We're going to be in every major
theatre in the United States,

533
00:32:05,064 --> 00:32:09,064
and this guy has to work
as a mailman for his income.

534
00:32:09,235 --> 00:32:12,035
The person who
won't speak up for himself

535
00:32:12,037 --> 00:32:13,904
finally finds his voice...

536
00:32:15,007 --> 00:32:18,570
...that kind of angry voice.

537
00:32:18,843 --> 00:32:23,814
Jerry is tired.
He's tired of losing.

538
00:32:23,816 --> 00:32:26,016
He's tired of being bullied,

539
00:32:26,018 --> 00:32:29,787
and he's not
going to take it any longer.

540
00:32:29,789 --> 00:32:32,456
Jerry writes letters...

541
00:32:32,458 --> 00:32:35,192
letters full of vitriol and spite,

542
00:32:35,194 --> 00:32:39,550
even putting a curse
on the Superman film.

543
00:32:39,564 --> 00:32:44,168
He curses Warner Brothers
and DC, and says,

544
00:32:44,170 --> 00:32:47,104
"Your Superman is built on lies."

545
00:32:47,106 --> 00:32:52,242
He writes, "My American dream
has turned into an American nightmare."

546
00:32:52,244 --> 00:32:55,212
He said, "I believed people.
I trusted people,

547
00:32:55,214 --> 00:32:56,914
and then they took it all away from me,

548
00:32:56,916 --> 00:32:59,116
and the courts didn't back me up."

549
00:32:59,118 --> 00:33:02,245
He said, "Our system is broken."

550
00:33:02,320 --> 00:33:04,588
Finally, he gets it all out

551
00:33:04,590 --> 00:33:08,525
and he sends it to every
newspaper in the country.

552
00:33:08,527 --> 00:33:10,861
Of course, nobody, you know,
does anything with it.

553
00:33:10,863 --> 00:33:12,930
They don't believe it...

554
00:33:12,931 --> 00:33:17,234
except one guy...
Neal Adams.

555
00:33:17,236 --> 00:33:18,836
Neal Adams infused comics

556
00:33:18,838 --> 00:33:22,606
with a sense of self-confidence and
swagger that wasn't there before.

557
00:33:22,608 --> 00:33:26,243
He understood
the value of creativity,

558
00:33:26,245 --> 00:33:30,722
and he had been around enough
people from the prior generation

559
00:33:30,757 --> 00:33:33,841
to recognize that they were not
getting their proper due.

560
00:33:34,119 --> 00:33:36,420
Ever since I got into comics,

561
00:33:36,422 --> 00:33:39,957
I had been asking about
Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster,

562
00:33:39,959 --> 00:33:43,193
and, uh, one day, there was
a letter waiting for me,

563
00:33:43,195 --> 00:33:45,996
and it was from Jerry Siegel...

564
00:33:46,331 --> 00:33:48,332
...and it was the whole story

565
00:33:48,334 --> 00:33:52,035
of what happened with Jerry and Joe,
from his point of view.

566
00:33:52,037 --> 00:33:54,571
It was devastating.

567
00:33:54,573 --> 00:33:58,475
The creators of Superman are no
longer associated with Superman?

568
00:33:58,477 --> 00:34:02,146
Hmm...
No. That's not right.

569
00:34:06,317 --> 00:34:10,220
By the mid 1970s,
the United States is hurting.

570
00:34:11,256 --> 00:34:13,557
Vietnam...

571
00:34:13,559 --> 00:34:16,460
Watergate...

572
00:34:16,462 --> 00:34:20,462
and a crumbling economy
have all taken their toll.

573
00:34:20,566 --> 00:34:24,167
Corporate greed has run amok.

574
00:34:25,069 --> 00:34:28,976
Once again, America needs a hero.

575
00:34:29,240 --> 00:34:32,075
The bicentennial is approaching,

576
00:34:32,077 --> 00:34:35,345
and the public wants to believe

577
00:34:35,347 --> 00:34:39,882
that the virtues of America
will be restored.

578
00:34:40,285 --> 00:34:43,420
And that's where Jerry Siegel
and Joe Shuster

579
00:34:43,422 --> 00:34:46,156
come back into the story.

580
00:34:46,158 --> 00:34:49,393
People now, in the comics community,
particularly like Neal Adams,

581
00:34:49,395 --> 00:34:52,129
sense that this is really unfair.

582
00:34:52,131 --> 00:34:57,534
$300,000...
to Mario Puzo?

583
00:34:57,536 --> 00:35:01,405
This guy, Jerry Siegel,
he's spitting ve...

584
00:35:01,407 --> 00:35:03,573
He hates these...
He's just "pshht!"

585
00:35:03,575 --> 00:35:06,710
You can't get a nice word
out of him. He's just angry.

586
00:35:06,712 --> 00:35:10,414
He created Superman!
Joe doesn't have $300!

587
00:35:10,416 --> 00:35:13,550
How does he get all that money,
and we get nothing?

588
00:35:13,552 --> 00:35:15,485
I know you guys are upset
about the movie,

589
00:35:15,487 --> 00:35:18,895
but I think you should look
at this as an opportunity.

590
00:35:19,257 --> 00:35:22,106
- How?
- Well, it just so happens that I talked

591
00:35:22,141 --> 00:35:24,061
to the president
of the International Press Corps,

592
00:35:24,063 --> 00:35:26,730
and he agreed to set up
a press conference for you guys,

593
00:35:26,732 --> 00:35:31,335
and when he does, the world is
finally gonna hear your story.

594
00:35:31,337 --> 00:35:35,205
These guys went to DC
and Warner Brothers,

595
00:35:35,207 --> 00:35:37,074
because Warner Brothers
owned DC,

596
00:35:37,076 --> 00:35:40,129
and just said,
"Look, you can't do this."

597
00:35:41,353 --> 00:35:44,014
For months,
Adams leads a media crusade,

598
00:35:44,016 --> 00:35:46,550
and the public is ready to listen.

599
00:35:46,552 --> 00:35:48,719
Something doesn't
have to be legal to be right,

600
00:35:48,721 --> 00:35:50,554
and it doesn't have to be right
to be legal.

601
00:35:50,556 --> 00:35:53,023
This is about justice.

602
00:35:53,025 --> 00:35:56,611
The people want to
right the wrong of what happened

603
00:35:56,612 --> 00:35:58,562
to Superman's creators.

604
00:35:58,564 --> 00:36:02,399
This is a story of two men
who dreamed up a super idea

605
00:36:02,401 --> 00:36:04,468
and then saw others
race away with it,

606
00:36:04,470 --> 00:36:06,737
faster than a speeding bullet.

607
00:36:06,739 --> 00:36:10,340
There's no courtroom in sight.

608
00:36:10,342 --> 00:36:13,827
It's the courtroom of public opinion.

609
00:36:14,679 --> 00:36:17,147
However much DC
may have been in the right

610
00:36:17,149 --> 00:36:19,750
in the case, legally...

611
00:36:19,752 --> 00:36:24,277
there is this sense in the general
public that this is not right.

612
00:36:25,427 --> 00:36:27,157
We do not want
to live in an America

613
00:36:27,159 --> 00:36:29,259
where people can
create something like this

614
00:36:29,261 --> 00:36:32,529
and other people
can get rich off of it.

615
00:36:32,531 --> 00:36:34,398
And so an agreement is reached.

616
00:36:34,400 --> 00:36:37,300
If there is any story
the American audience loves,

617
00:36:37,302 --> 00:36:40,137
it's the story
of the little man triumphant,

618
00:36:40,139 --> 00:36:43,507
the individual who whups up
on big government or big business.

619
00:36:43,509 --> 00:36:46,510
The publicity for Siegel
and Shuster was so heavy

620
00:36:46,512 --> 00:36:49,379
that Warner Communications,
current owners of Superman,

621
00:36:49,381 --> 00:36:53,250
decided to pay the two men
even though three courts had ruled

622
00:36:53,252 --> 00:36:57,166
that Siegel and Shuster
had no ownership.

623
00:36:57,388 --> 00:36:59,489
They end up
giving Siegel and Shuster

624
00:36:59,491 --> 00:37:03,660
what's essentially a pension.
They got enough to live off of.

625
00:37:03,662 --> 00:37:05,436
They seem pretty comfortable,
they can travel,

626
00:37:05,437 --> 00:37:09,464
and there's a sense that maybe
their fight wasn't in vain.

627
00:37:10,535 --> 00:37:12,402
Joe and Jerry
were fine with the settlement.

628
00:37:12,404 --> 00:37:14,671
They said,
"We love this. This is great,"

629
00:37:14,673 --> 00:37:21,242
and Neal Adams said "No."
He said, "We want the byline."

630
00:37:21,346 --> 00:37:25,346
I said to Warners,
"Look, you take care of these boys,

631
00:37:25,384 --> 00:37:27,551
and you will have
ambassadors of good will

632
00:37:27,553 --> 00:37:30,320
for anything you do with Superman.

633
00:37:30,322 --> 00:37:32,322
They're gonna be your friends.

634
00:37:32,324 --> 00:37:34,858
When you open the Superman movie,

635
00:37:34,860 --> 00:37:38,334
they'll be right there
with you, smiling."

636
00:37:42,801 --> 00:37:45,368
Both men are
invited to the world premiere

637
00:37:45,370 --> 00:37:48,672
of Superman: The Movie.

638
00:37:48,674 --> 00:37:52,175
After nearly 30 years of anguish,

639
00:37:52,177 --> 00:37:56,232
Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster
have arrived.

640
00:37:58,783 --> 00:38:02,619
Jerry and Joe
had gotten some money...

641
00:38:02,621 --> 00:38:06,698
but on this night,
they would receive so much more.

642
00:38:11,429 --> 00:38:14,164
For on this night...

643
00:38:14,166 --> 00:38:18,886
Superman is theirs once again.

644
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:50,867
They got their byline back.

645
00:38:50,869 --> 00:38:55,405
You know, for Siegel and Shuster,
after 28, 29 years,

646
00:38:55,407 --> 00:38:58,642
they're seeing
their names on film

647
00:38:58,644 --> 00:39:00,177
as the creators of this character.

648
00:39:00,179 --> 00:39:03,514
That is a big thing for them.
That means a lot.

649
00:39:03,515 --> 00:39:05,448
It's vindication.

650
00:39:05,450 --> 00:39:08,752
Those two guys
who implanted the imaginations

651
00:39:08,754 --> 00:39:11,421
of generations of children since then

652
00:39:11,423 --> 00:39:13,790
and generations of children to come,

653
00:39:13,792 --> 00:39:17,627
finally got acknowledged for that.

654
00:39:17,629 --> 00:39:20,330
Siegel and Shuster believed

655
00:39:20,332 --> 00:39:22,666
creative rights
belong to creative people,

656
00:39:22,668 --> 00:39:25,769
and they had to fight for it.

657
00:39:25,771 --> 00:39:28,926
Everybody who makes
a living dreaming about

658
00:39:28,961 --> 00:39:31,539
people who put on capes
and masks and helping others

659
00:39:31,577 --> 00:39:34,477
bend a knee at the altar
of Siegel and Shuster.

660
00:39:34,479 --> 00:39:37,814
Without them, you have nothing.

661
00:39:37,816 --> 00:39:41,952
Superman: The Movie
is released in December 1978,

662
00:39:41,954 --> 00:39:43,820
and is a blockbuster smash,

663
00:39:43,822 --> 00:39:48,572
earning $300 million
during its theatrical run.

664
00:39:54,232 --> 00:39:55,732
In the decade that follows,

665
00:39:55,734 --> 00:39:59,269
Joe and Jerry are comfortable,
if not content.

666
00:40:01,272 --> 00:40:03,807
They live on the California coastline,

667
00:40:03,809 --> 00:40:07,590
just a few houses
away from each other.

668
00:40:08,713 --> 00:40:11,191
And that's the best, you now?
So at the end,

669
00:40:11,226 --> 00:40:16,286
it's not the court case or
controversy about Superman.

670
00:40:16,288 --> 00:40:19,422
It's just two best friends.

671
00:40:19,424 --> 00:40:26,304
One of the big life lessons from this
is "creator rights matter."

672
00:40:26,765 --> 00:40:29,499
A young person who's aware
of Siegel and Shuster,

673
00:40:29,501 --> 00:40:33,501
they now know what they
have to have in a row.

674
00:40:33,672 --> 00:40:36,668
Everybody now fights for their rights.

675
00:40:37,708 --> 00:40:42,879
The business has changed
because everybody learned

676
00:40:42,881 --> 00:40:46,260
from Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster.

677
00:40:48,286 --> 00:40:49,686
Out of a kitchen,

678
00:40:49,688 --> 00:40:53,688
two kids create
the world's first superhero.

679
00:40:55,060 --> 00:40:58,995
It's a fable
almost as fantastical as flying.

680
00:41:00,464 --> 00:41:05,669
Theirs is a tale of struggle and
heartache, but also of perseverance.

681
00:41:06,804 --> 00:41:11,600
They made it,
and the world will always know...

682
00:41:12,376 --> 00:41:18,346
Superman,
created by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster.

683
00:41:28,092 --> 00:41:32,607
_

684
00:41:32,611 --> 00:41:36,828
__

685
00:41:36,829 --> 00:41:43,723
_

686
